assets.description:
Concept of the "Grace" in the 3rd dimension -from Terry Goodkind's series of books, The Sword of Truth.

The original picture you can find here: http://vignette3.wikia.nocookie.net/sot/images/c/c0/Grace2.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20100323011505

From the text, "Though a Grace appears simple, it represents the whole of everything. The outer circle represents the beginning of the underworld -the infinite world of the dead. Out beyond the circle, the underworld, there is nothing else; there is only forever. The square represents the Veil, separating the world of the dead, from the world of the living (the inner circle). The star at the center of it all is the light -the Creator, with rays of His gift of magic coming from the light to pass through all the boundaries... 

The Grace is the depiction of the continuum of the Gift."

assets.name: assets/3A01fMN4zyG
assets.description:
Find an image you would like to import in a 16:9 Aspect Ratio.
Here is a list of all 16:9 Resolutions. https://pacoup.com/2011/06/12/list-of-true-169-resolutions/
When uploading back into Google Poly the limit on resolution size is 4096 x 4096. The Max 16:9 resolution possible is 4096 x 2304, however you will find many more pictures at 4K UHD resolution of 3840 x 2160. 

Download the OBJ from this page.

You will get a .Zip file such as. (poster_OBJ_3A01fMN4zyG_3QBWft_RqDn.zip)
Unzip this to a folder and you will find 3 files. (poster.jpg, poster.mtl, poster.obj)
You can now delete the original poster.jpg and place your new image in this folder.
Then rename the new image poster.jpg.
Now you can Upload the 3 files back onto Google Poly you do not need to re-zip them.

First click the upload icon at the top of the page on Google Poly next to the search bar.

A popup will display which you can drag and drop the 3 files here or click the link to select files from your computer.

If you click the link be sure to select all 3 files and then click open.

It should take a moment to upload and then display a grid with no errors displayed to the right. You will not see the image immediately.

Click anywhere in the display window and drag to reveal the image.
